n characters in the Latin American fiction known as Magical Realism embody a playful and spontaneous approach to life and literature. The relationship of the magical to the real in Latin American fiction is, the book argues, comparable to the 'let's pretend' world and toys in play. The act of playing and living in these novels is a re-creative experience - a concept which has not been adequately explored in contemporary criticism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPicaresque literature, SpanishxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267852140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442678521423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442678521.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK